<br>
pretty sure the only job a moderator would have is to make sure content of posts didnt violate ez board policy, and any additional policies set in place by the board admin.  this board could be about WC3, bass fishing, chess, war on terrorism etc and none of that would change the primary duties of a board mod.<br>
<br>
additionally, its not the job of a moderator to comment on subject matter which does not conflict with policy. moderators should not be giving their opinions on posters, their material etc unless it is in some form of violation.<br>
<br>
think you are referring to editorial commentation, in that case yes a knowledge of the subject matter would make a difference.<br>
<br>
if wizard01 posts about how they should not change ragefire spawns, (as long as no board policies were violated) the moderator should remain silent. that is the inherent flaw of having a member of the community being a moderator. where as a neutral third party could easily fill that role and refrain from adding commentary.<br>
<br>
In a way its like a news reporter, have you heard a news reporter (not editor or special commentary edition) break the bounds of impartiality? no. they will say police arrested 80year old lady for offense A, not that they think the police were stupid for arresting said lady. therein lies the difference.<br>
<br>
If you cannot see the benifits of having an impartial non connected person to the community acting as impartial moderator then dont know what more can be said. any member of the community who is a moderator will be liked and disliked based on ingame play, or commentary on others posts.<br>
<br>
a truly impartial moderator can fully refrain from commenting on anyones post no matter how strongly they agree or disagree with the content (as long as it is not in violation of policy) this should be what the majority would want in a moderator. <p>Gathrintain Druidslayer <Da Bashin' Iggles>
